There is only one correct way to interpret Goedel’s Incompleteness results. Verena Huber-Dyson gives the correct interpretation, albeit informally, in her excellent Edge article, GÖDEL AND THE NATURE OF MATHEMATICAL TRUTH II. I have already explained Goedel’s First Incompleteness Theorem in Wes Hansen's answer to Is the following sentence equivalent to Gödel gamma sentence: "It is unprovable a sentence which says that a sentence is unprovable"? and I will reproduce that discussion here; but first allow me to lay a bit of groundwork. The modern way we deal with truth arose primarily due to Alfred Tarski’s work, which resulted in Model Theory; you can read a bit about it in the Alfred Tarski entry on Stanford’s Encyclopedia of Philosophy (see the subject heading, truth). What follows is largely from A Problem Course in Mathematical Logic, which is not a very good textbook unless you already know logic or are engaged with an instructor. It’s perfect for this discussion however. What we need from that book is simply an understanding of what the logical symbols, [math]\vdash[/math] and [math]\models[/math], actually mean. Okay, so we need a couple of definitions from A Problem Course. From page 24, we define the symbols used in a First-order Language: Definition 5.1. The symbols of a first-order language [math]\mathcal{L}[/math] include: Parentheses: [math]([/math] and [math])[/math].Connectives: [math]
eg[/math] and [math]\implies[/math] (negation and implication, respectively).Quantifier: [math] orall[/math] (for any or for all).Variables: [math]v_0, v_1, v_2,..., v_n,...[/math]Equality: [math]=[/math].A (possibly empty) set of constant symbols.For each [math]k \geq 1[/math], a (possibly empty) set of [math]k[/math]-place function symbols (these are often called operations).For each [math]k \geq 1[/math], a (possibly empty) set of [math]k[/math]-place relation (or predicate) symbols.From page 33, we define a structure for a language: Definition 6.1. A structure [math]\mathcal{M}[/math] for [math]\mathcal{L}[/math] consists of the following: A non-empty set [math]M[/math], often written as |[math]\mathcal{M}[/math]|, called the universe of [math]\mathcal{M}[/math].For each constant symbol [math]c[/math] of [math]\mathcal{L}[/math], an element [math]c^\mathcal{M}[/math] of [math]\mathcal{M}[/math].For each [math]k[/math]-place function symbol [math]f[/math] of [math]\mathcal{L}[/math], a function [math]f^\mathcal{M} : \mathcal{M}_k \implies \mathcal{M}[/math], i.e. a [math]k[/math]-place function on [math]\mathcal{M}[/math].For each [math]k[/math]-place relation symbol [math]P[/math] of [math]\mathcal{L}[/math], a relation [math]P^ \mathcal{M} \subseteq M^k[/math], i.e. a [math]k[/math]-place relation on [math]\mathcal{M}[/math].Okay, so that defines a structure of a logical language, a formal language. These structures have no semantical content. To give them semantical content we must interpret the symbols in such a way that all of the axioms of our structure are true at the same time; this results in a model of our structure. So now, suppose we have a language we call Peano Arithmetic, [math]\mathcal{L}_{PA}[/math], and suppose we have some sentence about Peano Arithmetic, [math]q[/math]. Then the sentence [math]\mathcal{L}_{PA} \models q[/math] simply says that there is an interpretation of the symbols such that the axioms of our structure AND the sentence [math]q[/math] are true at the same time; the sentence [math]\mathcal{L}_{PA} \vdash q[/math] simply says that there is a formal deduction from the axioms of our language which concludes with the sentence [math]q[/math] or, in other words, there is a proof of [math]q[/math] from our axioms. Okay, with that out of the way, I’m going to simply reproduce that other answer of mine here and add an explanation of the Second Incompleteness Theorem. No, that would be a tautology and you can prove tautologies from the empty set. An example of an actual Goedel sentence could be the binary Goldbach conjecture. Let [math]P[/math] be the set of all prime numbers and let [math]E[/math] be the set of all even positive integers greater than two. Then the binary Goldbach conjecture says that for any [math]e \in E[/math] there exists [math]p_1, p_2 \in P[/math] such that [math]e = p_1 + p_2[/math]. Many believe this to be not only undecidable but also an instance of incompleteness. But the actual content of Goedel’s sentence [math]g[/math] doesn’t really matter other than it is a sentence about Peano Arithmetic. Goedel’s result is in the domain of meta-mathematics and is really a statement about First-Order Logic (FOL) and the concepts truth and proof which accompany FOL. For a great long time it was believed by most if not all mathematicians that our first-order concepts truth and proof were equivalent; this belief largely motivated the search for soundness and completeness theorems: Soundness Theorem: If [math]α[/math] is a sentence and [math]∆[/math] is a set of sentences such that [math]∆ \vdash α[/math], then [math]∆ \models α[/math]. In English, if there is a proof from [math]∆[/math] which concludes with [math]α[/math], then there is an interpretation which makes all of the sentences in [math]∆ \cup α[/math] true at the same time. Completeness Theorem: If [math]α[/math] is a sentence and [math]∆[/math] is a set of sentences such that [math]∆ \models α[/math], then [math]∆ \vdash α[/math]. In English, if there is an interpretation which makes all of the sentences in [math]∆ \cup α[/math] true at the same time, then there is a proof from [math]∆[/math] which concludes with [math]α[/math]. By the Law of Biconditional, these demonstrate equivalence between proof and truth, truth here represented by Tarski’s Model Theoretic method. Tarski was the founder of Model Theory and Model Theory was largely motivated by Goedel’s results and Tarski’s own closely related Undefinability Theorem. When we prove Soundness and Completeness of FOL in an introductory course, we use an arbitrary set of sentences, meaning these theorems are completely general, i.e. they hold for any possible axiomatic system that FOL could be utilized with. While investigating the so-called decision problem, Goedel, using very creative meta-mathematical techniques, demonstrated that this is not true. Let [math]\mathcal{L}_{PA}[/math] be the language of Peano Arithmetic. Then Goedel proved what is today called the Fixed-Point Lemma or the Diagonalization Lemma which leads straightaway to: [math]\mathcal{L}_{PA} \vdash (g \iff \mathcal{L}_{PA} 
