eg g[/math] can be proven from those axioms and the above discussion tells us why. Incompleteness, then, is a Corollary to a much more general phenomenon, Turing’s Uncomputability. For a really great explication of Goedel’s results, see On Fixed-Points, Diagonalization, and Self-Reference. [end other answer] Okay, now, to understand the Second Incompleteness result, that a recursive, consistent system cannot prove it’s own consistency, it is only necessary to realize that an inconsistent system “blows up,” i. e. it becomes useless because it will prove anything, including any sentence [math]g[/math] and its negation. With this realization, it is quite simple to show a logical equivalence between Goedel’s sentence [math]g[/math] and the sentence, “[math]PA[/math] is consistent.” If [math]PA[/math] can prove it’s own consistency then, it could also prove the sentence [math]g[/math] and we have shown that that is impossible. Do you understand that? The idea is, saying that a system is consistent is the same thing, logically, as saying that there exists sentences unprovable by the system.
